       <div class="homeTitle">
        Trauma Blog
       </div>
       <ul class="news">
        <div class="BlogPreview">
         <div class="BlogPTitle">
          <a href="/education-research/traumatic-stresspoints/2018-june/istss-statement-on-the-importance-of-keeping-famil.aspx">
           ISTSS Statement on the Importance of Keeping Families Together and the Traumatic Stress Associated with Child Separation from Parents and Caregivers
          </a>
         </div>
         <div>
          <span class="BlogPDate">
           06/23/2018
          </span>
          by
         </div>
         <div class="BlogPBody TextContent">
          ISTSS is concerned about the impact of removal of immigrant and asylum-seeking children from their parents and caregivers, as has been the recent practice and policy in the U.S. Decades of research and clinical knowledge have repeatedly demonstrated that the relationship with a parent or primary caregiver is critical to a childâ€™s sense of self, safety, and trust. Separation from caregivers during stressful and traumatic situations can cause irreparable harm in itself and often has longstanding and severe effects on children.
         </div>
        </div>
        <div class="BlogPreview">
         <div class="BlogPTitle">
          <a href="/education-research/traumatic-stresspoints/2018-june/crossing-the-finish-line-in-tf-cbt-factors-associa.aspx">
           Crossing the Finish Line in TF-CBT: Factors Associated with Treatment Completion for Families Following Alleged Child Abuse
          </a>
         </div>
         <div>
          <span class="BlogPDate">
           06/01/2018
          </span>
          by Anna Stagg, MEd, PhD &amp; Amanda NeMoyer, J.D., Ph.D.
         </div>
         <div class="BlogPBody TextContent">
          Childhood physical and/or sexual abuseâ€”something more than 100,000 youth in the United States have experiencedâ€”has been observed to detrimentally impact youth across biological, psychological, and social domains, and may lead to posttraumatic stress and trauma
         </div>
        </div>
        <div class="BlogPreview">
         <div class="BlogPTitle">
          <a href="/education-research/traumatic-stresspoints/2018-june/trauma-and-diversity-the-role-of-health-care-in-ad.aspx">
           Trauma and Diversity: The Role of Health Care in Addressing Adverse Childhood Experiences (ACEs) Among Racial and Ethnic Minority Youth
          </a>
         </div>
         <div>
          <span class="BlogPDate">
           06/01/2018
          </span>
          by Chris Sexton, PhD, MSW, and Briana Woods-Jaeger, PhD, MS
         </div>
         <div class="BlogPBody TextContent">
          Toxic stress resulting from chronic exposure to adverse childhood experiences (ACEs), including trauma exposure, parent mental health problems, and family dysfunction, can lead to numerous health, social, and behavioral problems throughout the lifespan (Anda et al., 2006).
